  <!-- Section: Common Mistakes -->
  <section id="mistakes" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Bringing International Insurance</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">The most common mistake. Cigna, Allianz International, SafetyWing, and other international insurers are NOT accepted for German residence permits. You must have German public or approved German private insurance. Don't waste time and money on the wrong coverage.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Opening Blocked Account Too Late</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">International transfers to Sperrkonto accounts take 1-2 weeks. If you wait until your visa appointment is scheduled, you risk delays or having to reschedule. Open your blocked account immediately after receiving admission.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Ignoring German Language</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Even for English-taught programs, daily life in Germany requires some German. Landlords, bureaucrats, shops, and social situations often involve German. Learning basics before arrival and continuing in Germany significantly improves your experience.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Missing Registration Deadlines</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">You must register at the Ausländerbehörde within 90 days of arrival. Missing this deadline creates serious problems for your legal status. Mark it in your calendar and gather documents early—German offices often have long wait times for appointments.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Waiting Until 30 for Insurance</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">If you're approaching 30, enroll in public insurance BEFORE your birthday. Once you're 30, public insurance becomes unavailable for students. If you're already enrolled before 30, you can continue coverage. Don't miss this deadline.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Healthcare in Germany -->
  <section id="healthcare" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Healthcare in Germany</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Germany has one of the world's best healthcare systems. With your student health insurance (public or approved private), you have access to excellent doctors, specialists, and hospitals. The system is efficient and high-quality.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">What's Covered by Public Insurance</h3>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
      <div class="border border-green-200 bg-green-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-green-900 mb-3">Covered Services</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-green-800">
          <li>✓ Doctor visits (GP and specialists)</li>
          <li>✓ Hospital treatment</li>
          <li>✓ Prescription medications (small copay)</li>
          <li>✓ Mental health therapy</li>
          <li>✓ Basic dental care</li>
          <li>✓ Maternity care</li>
          <li>✓ Preventive checkups</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-amber-200 bg-amber-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-3">Partial or Extra Coverage</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-amber-800">
          <li>• Dental crowns/bridges (50-65% covered)</li>
          <li>• Glasses/contacts (children only, mostly)</li>
          <li>• Alternative medicine (limited)</li>
          <li>• Single hospital rooms (extra insurance)</li>
          <li>• Some vaccinations (travel vaccines)</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">How to Access Healthcare</h3>

    <div class="space-y-4 mb-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Step 1: Get Your Insurance Card</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">After enrolling in public insurance (TK, AOK, etc.), you'll receive an electronic health card (Gesundheitskarte). This is your key to accessing healthcare—keep it with you.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Step 2: Find a Hausarzt (GP)</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Register with a general practitioner in your area. While not mandatory, having a regular Hausarzt is practical. They coordinate your care and provide referrals to specialists.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Step 3: Book Appointments</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Call the doctor's office directly or use the Doctolib app. Specialist appointments may have waits (2-6 weeks for non-urgent). For urgent issues, many cities have walk-in clinics.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Emergencies</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Call 112 for ambulance/fire/emergency. Hospital emergency rooms (Notaufnahme) treat emergencies. For after-hours non-emergencies, call 116 117 for the doctor-on-call service.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4 mt-6">
      <p class="text-blue-800">
        <strong>University health services:</strong> Most German universities have student health centers (Studentenwerk) offering medical and psychological support. These are often easier to access than external doctors and understand student-specific issues.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is tuition really free in Germany?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes, at public universities. You only pay a semester fee (€150-350) covering administration, student union, and often a public transport pass. Private universities charge tuition (€10,000-40,000/year). About 90% of German students attend public universities.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I use Cigna, Allianz International, or SafetyWing in Germany?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          No. German authorities require insurance meeting German standards—either public (gesetzliche) or approved German private insurance. International plans are not accepted for residence permits. You must switch to German insurance.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What is a blocked account (Sperrkonto)?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          A blocked account is a special German bank account proving you can support yourself. You deposit €11,208 (one year's living costs) and can only withdraw €934/month. Providers include Fintiba (€89 fee), Expatrio (€49 fee), and Deutsche Bank (free but slower).
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I work while studying in Germany?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes. International students can work 120 full days or 240 half days per year without a separate work permit. Mini-jobs (€538/month max) don't count toward this limit. During semester breaks, you can work full-time.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I stay after graduation?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes—Germany offers an 18-month job-search visa after graduation, one of the most generous in the world. Find a job related to your studies, and you can switch to a work visa. This makes Germany excellent for building a career in Europe.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I need to speak German?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          For English-taught programs, German isn't required for admission. However, daily life (housing, bureaucracy, shopping, social) is easier with German. Many employers also prefer German speakers. Learning at least basics significantly improves your experience.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Final Verdict -->
  <section id="verdict" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Final Verdict</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Germany offers one of the world's best deals for international students: free tuition at public universities, excellent education quality, affordable living costs, and an 18-month job-search visa after graduation. The trade-off is navigating German bureaucracy and meeting strict insurance requirements.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4">
      The insurance requirement is non-negotiable but straightforward: for students under 30, German public insurance (~€110/month) is mandatory and excellent. It provides comprehensive coverage with no deductibles for most services. For students 30+, approved private insurance fills the gap.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-6">
      Don't make the mistake of bringing international insurance—it won't be accepted. Plan ahead, open your blocked account early, and enroll in German insurance before your visa appointment. The preparation is worth it for access to free, high-quality education in the heart of Europe.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-3">Bottom Line</h3>
      <p class="text-primary-800 mb-4">
        Germany offers free tuition, excellent education, and strong career prospects. You must have German-compliant health insurance—public for under 30, approved private for 30+. International insurance won't work. Get the right coverage, and you'll have access to one of the world's best healthcare systems.
      </p>
